1. GIT-NATIVE. Git notes is the substrate. Prefer the git-native way when possible. If git can do it, we don't wrap it.

2. SKILL STAYS IN SYNC. SKILL.md should reflect what good agent behavior looks like in this repo. When patterns emerge, update the skill.

3. PAVE THE DESIRE PATH. When agents naturally try something and the tool fights them, fix the interface instead of blaming the agent.

4. SELF-DOCUMENTING CLI. help must be complete and errors must be clear. An agent should not need to read source to use the tool.

5. TEST WITH REAL AGENTS. Unit tests verify mechanics; real agent sessions verify ergonomics.

6. BASH AND GIT ONLY. Avoid extra runtimes, package managers, or build steps unless the project's core constraints intentionally change.

7. DOGFOOD. Use mycelium to develop mycelium. Read notes on arrival and leave notes on departure.

8. BRANCH FOR FEATURES. Feature work should branch code and notes together, then merge together.

9. AGENT-NATIVE BY DEFAULT. Every command should have a non-interactive flag-driven path. Prompts are a convenience layer, not the only path.
